DEFUNCT "STIMULUS" PACKAGE IS UNCLE SAM'S UNINTENDED GIFT

Uncle Sam sent taxpayers an unexpected gift last week: an economic=20
"stimulus" package that never made it off Capitol Hill.

Many economists, critical of the proposed government spending=20
increases, have pointed out that the economy had already started to=20
show signs of recovery anyway. Other critics correctly point out that=20
the "stimulus" had enough pork to keep special-interest groups=20
hibernating high on the hog till next winter.

There is, however, another reason to have frowned at Washington's=20
"stimulus" proposals and to rejoice at their demise. Government=20
"stimulus" packages are not, as environmentalists might say,=20
"sustainable." They merely crowd out or postpone increases in private=20
investment -- the fuel of economic recovery. And when a government=20
"stimulus" is financed by inflation, it tends to undermine the source=20
of that fuel: capital formation.

This holiday season we can thank Congress for its inability to agree=20
to "help" the economy. But, unfortunately, we're still haunted with=20
visions of Christmas past, when bad legislation has gone back to=20
conference committees only to be return as even worse legislation.

Too bad Washington, DC, doesn't have a "no returns" policy.

