A CHRISTMAS REFLECTION

Christmas, a holiday rooted in both Christianity and pre-Christian=20
celebrations of the winter solstice, is also an appropriate time to=20
reflect upon the secular values that have helped Western civilization=20
over the course of two tumultuous millennia. Among these values:=20
freedom of conscience, peace on Earth, and goodwill toward men.

These values transcend any particular religion; they are in fact=20
articulated in varying degrees by most of the world's religions. Yet=20
they have found their fullest expression in the West. Why?

Because in Western culture more than in any other, the individual counts.

"This empowerment of the individual is unique to Western=20
civilization," writes Paul Craig Roberts.

And it is this individualist precept -- respect for the dignity and=20
worth of each human life -- that holds the key to understanding the=20
unique institutions of the West.

The West's individualism, writes Roberts, "permits an individual=20
person to put his or her foot down, to take a stand on principle, to=20
become a reformer and take on injustice.... It has made the=20
individual a citizen equal in rights to all other citizens, protected=20
from tyrannical government by the rule of law and free speech."

Just as freedom in the West has unleashed in the marketplace the=20
progressive forces of what one economist termed "creative=20
destruction," so freedom in the West has unleashed a similar=20
phenomenon in the marketplace of ideas. This perhaps is the West's=20
supreme paradox (and achievement) -- its tradition of questioning=20
even tradition itself.

Concludes Roberts: "Be we religious or be we not, our celebration of=20
Christ's birthday celebrates a religion that made us masters of our=20
souls and of our political life on Earth. Such a religion as this is=20
worth holding onto even by atheists."

